#: ../../../extensions.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Discover how to extend Spack's core functionality by creating custom "
"commands and plugins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:11
msgid "Custom Extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:13
msgid ""
"*Spack extensions* allow you to add custom subcommands to the ``spack`` "
"command. This is extremely useful when developing and maintaining a command "
"whose purpose is too specific to be included in the Spack codebase. It's "
"also useful for evolving a command through its early stages before starting "
"a discussion to merge it upstream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:17
msgid ""
"From Spack's point of view, an extension is any path in your filesystem that "
"respects the following naming and layout for files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:19
msgid ""
"spack-scripting/ # The top level directory must match the format 'spack-"
"{extension_name}'\n"
"├── pytest.ini # Optional file if the extension ships its own tests\n"
"├── scripting # Folder that may contain modules that are needed for the "
"extension commands\n"
"│   ├── cmd # Folder containing extension commands\n"
"│   │   └── filter.py # A new command that will be available\n"
"│   └── functions.py # Module with internal details\n"
"├── tests # Tests for this extension\n"
"│   ├── conftest.py\n"
"│   └── test_filter.py\n"
"└── templates # Templates that may be needed by the extension"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:32
msgid ""
"In the example above, the extension is named *scripting*. It adds an "
"additional command (``spack filter``) and unit tests to verify its behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:35
msgid ""
"The extension can import any core Spack module in its implementation. When "
"loaded by the ``spack`` command, the extension itself is imported as a "
"Python package in the ``spack.extensions`` namespace. In the example above, "
"since the extension is named \"scripting\", the corresponding Python module "
"is ``spack.extensions.scripting``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:39
msgid ""
"The code for this example extension can be obtained by cloning the "
"corresponding git repository:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:41
msgid "$ git -C /tmp clone https://github.com/spack/spack-scripting.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:46
msgid "Configure Spack to Use Extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:48
msgid ""
"To make your current Spack instance aware of extensions you should add their "
"root paths to ``config.yaml``. In the case of our example, this means "
"ensuring that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:51
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  extensions:\n"
"  - /tmp/spack-scripting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:57
msgid ""
"is part of your configuration file. Once this is set up, any command that "
"the extension provides will be available from the command line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../extensions.rst:60
msgid ""
"$ spack filter --help\n"
"usage: spack filter [-h] [--installed | --not-installed]\n"
"                    [--explicit | --implicit] [--output OUTPUT]\n"
"                    ...\n"
"\n"
"filter specs based on their properties\n"
"\n"
"positional arguments:\n"
"  specs            specs to be filtered\n"
"\n"
"optional arguments:\n"
"  -h, --help       show this help message and exit\n"
"  --installed      select installed specs\n"
"  --not-installed  select specs that are not yet installed\n"
"  --explicit       select specs that were installed explicitly\n"
"  --implicit       select specs that are not installed or were installed "
"implicitly\n"
"  --output OUTPUT  where to dump the result"
msgstr ""

